rate limits, permission errors, or formatting problems. There's also a workflow-level consideration: if the diff is too large and comment posting is skipped, should the summary also be skipped?\n\nThis has Agentic elements since it includes LLM calls, but the core question is whether the entire workflow completes without intervention. It's also Workflow-level since it spans multiple agentic steps—analyzing the diff, posting comments, and generating the summary—as a coordinated sequence. The key question is whether multiple LLM calls are involved. The agent likely calls an LLM to identify issues from the diff, then potentially makes additional calls to generate inline comments and a summary—or reuses the initial analysis for those outputs. Either way, this involves orchestrating multiple steps: parsing the diff, analyzing for problems, posting comments at specific locations, and aggregating findings into a summary comment.\n\nThe test validates the full sequence working end-to-end without intervention, including the state machine (ensuring comments post before the summary, handling failures gracefully). Since it requires coordinating multiple LLM-dependent operations and verifying their correct ordering and completion, this is a Workflow-level test. way through, the workflow should handle it gracefully. You need a real PR or realistic simulation to verify the entire flow works end-to-end.\n\nThe probabilities lean heavily toward Workflow (0.7) with some possibility of Agentic (0.2), since the orchestration of multiple dependent steps is what matters most for catching real failures.\n\nFor behavior 1, the key is verifying that the LLM receives only the changed lines as context, not the entire file. I'd set up a test with a large file where only a small section was modified, then confirm the analysis focuses on just that diff region rather than processing all 100 lines.\n\nThe tricky part is deciding whether to mock the LLM call. If you mock it, you can inspect what input the agent actually passes—checking the data flow directly. But the real risk is that the agent sends full file content and the LLM returns findings scattered across unchanged lines. To catch that, you'd need to either verify the findings reference only changed lines, or use a real LLM call to see how it actually behaves with the full context.\n\nI think the approach should be: mock the diff fetching, provide a realistic PR with specific line changes, then verify the agent's output only addresses those changed lines. This is Integration-level testing since it coordinates multiple components—diff retrieval and analysis scoping—without testing the LLM itself.\n\nFor the second behavior about inline comments in the diff view, the phrase \"in the diff view on the pull request\" implies you need to validate this against the actual PR. You could potentially do this at Integration level by mocking the PR API and thoroughly checking the parameters being sent—specifically that comments are posted to the correct line positions in the diff. The real failure would surface if the comment gets posted to the wrong line or the wrong diff section.\n\nHowever, there's a distinction: mocking the API validates the parameters are correct, but doesn't confirm the comment actually renders in the right place on the PR itself. For a pragmatic approach, Unit tests could verify line number calculation logic, Integration tests could mock the API and validate file/line/commit parameters, and System tests could post to a real PR to confirm visual placement. The minimum level to catch actual failures depends on whether you trust the PR API's handling or need end-to-end verification.\n\nGiven the issue specifically calls out \"in the diff view on the pull request,\" System testing feels safer, though Integration with rigorous mock validation could suffice.\n\nFor behavior 5, the full sequence involves reading the diff, analyzing it (likely with an LLM call), posting inline comments, and posting